\f0\b\fs28 \cf0 4.2 Cross-Organization Interactions (Aircraft Sharing)\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa240\partightenfactor0

\f1\b0\fs24 \cf0 While organizations are isolated, the system supports 
\f0\b controlled cross-org linking
\f1\b0  for aircraft sharing:\
\pard\tx220\tx720\pardeftab720\li720\fi-720\partightenfactor0
\ls3\ilvl0\cf0 \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 \outl0\strokewidth0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec2 An 
\f0\b owner
\f1\b0  in Org A can share an aircraft with a 
\f0\b mechanic
\f1\b0  who has a standalone account (Org B or personal workspace)\
\ls3\ilvl0\kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 \outl0\strokewidth0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec2 This creates an 
\f4\fs26 aircraft_access
\f1\fs24  record \'97 the mechanic sees the aircraft in their portal, but it still 
\f0\b belongs to Org A
\f1\b0 \
\ls3\ilvl0\kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 \outl0\strokewidth0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec2 The owner in Org A can revoke this at any time\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa240\partightenfactor0
\cf0 This is the only cross-org data flow permitted. No other data crosses org boundaries.\
